Phase 1¶

There are several ways to get along with missing data.When the rate of missing data in a feature is remarkable and it can cause great error in our conclusion it is better to completly delete that feature.But when there are only a few number of missing data it is better to replace them by a value. One of the topic in this case is "Deductive Imputation" which contains the algorithms that replace missing data with a statistical value representing the whole data. We can replace Nan values in dataframe with various variables. First, we can use mean/median of the feature for replacement. This is helpful for replacing small amount of missing data which are not far from each other.

In these plots we represent missing data replaced values by red color.

In [80]:
## Missing data replace by Mean
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sub = df['LotFrontage'].isnull()
k = df['LotFrontage']
k = k.fillna(df['LotFrontage'].mean())
colors = {True:"Red", False:"Blue"}
ax.scatter(k, df['SalePrice'], c=df['LotFrontage'].isnull().map(colors), alpha=0.3, edgecolors='none')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [41]:
## Missing data replace by Mean
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sub = df['LotFrontage'].isnull()
k = df['LotFrontage']

x = df['LotFrontage']
x = x.fillna(x.mean())
y = df['SalePrice']
b, m = polyfit(x, y, 1)
plt.plot(x, y, '.')
plt.plot(x, b + m * x, '-')

plt.show()

We can also draw a linear regression in the plot and replace each missing value with the pairing match point on the line. Using this method we can predict our missing values more efficiently and make a better prediction.

All the missing data handled!!¶

Normalizing a group of data means to divide it by a norm of the data. It also often refers to rescaling by the minimum and range of the data, to make all the elements lie between 0 and 1.

Standardizing a group of data means subtracting a measure of location and dividing by a measure of scale.

Standardizing the features around the center and 0 with a standard deviation of 1 is important when we compare measurements that have different units. Variables that are measured at different scales do not contribute equally to the analysis and might end up creating a bais.

Similarly, the goal of normalization is to change the values of numeric columns in the dataset to a common scale, without distorting differences in the ranges of values. It is required only when features have different ranges.

According to our dataset we have variety of feature values that should have a same effect on the result. For example the range of the feature OverallQual changes from 1 to 10, Although the range of the feature GrLivArea is between 334 and 5642 Assuming both features has an equal effect on the price.

In [95]:
print("Range of OverallQual =",df['OverallQual'].min(),',' ,df['OverallQual'].max())
print("Range of GrLivArea =",df['GrLivArea'].min(),',' ,df['GrLivArea'].max())

Range of GrLivArea = 334 , 5642

In order to get along with categorical features we convert objects to category and then coded them, so all of the features are in numerical order now. There are several ways to encode features. Method we are using here is called Lable Encoding. In this method each variable mapped to a number starting from 0. There are many other methods like One-Hot encoding, binary encoding, target encoding, effect encoding and etc.

For deciding to remove some rows we are going to take a look at feature relation list again.

In the next step we have to split our data into test and train subsets. Basically, we have 3 ways which is similar to each other in some ways.

The first one is to randomly choose m samples out of n we have, train them and set the other samples for testing our answer. The optimal rate of m/n approaches to 66%. It means to choos 2/3thrd of your dataset for training and the other 1/3thrd for test.

The second one called K-fold Cross Validation. In this method all samples divided into k groups of equal size(if possible) called fold. Each time we use k-1 fold as a training part and the last one for the test. Typically, people use k=5 or k=10 as a parameter of this method.

The third one which is very similar with previous method is called Leave One Out Cross Validation. In k-fold C.V if we assume that k is equal to n which means for all samples we try to use it as test for one time. After that, we get test performance for all of our samples and this is how LOO CV works.

Overfitting and Underfitting¶

Before looking at underfitting and overfitting lets take a look at two important terms in data science:

1. Bias: Assumptions made by a model to make a function easier to learn.
2. Variance: Error that take place when we change the train data using same learning model.

Underfitting¶

Underfitting means that the model we creat for learning the data is not well enough for predicting every new data. It usually takes place when we have less data to train or when our model is linear and our data is not. Underfitting can be avoided by using more data and also reducing the features by feature selection. In other word underfitting is High bias and low variance model.

Overfitting¶

Overfitting means that the model we creat for learning the data trains with a lot of data which causes the model to learn from noises. Then the model does not categorize the data correctly, because of too many details and noise. It accures when the dataset is too huge or our model is too complex. In other word, overfitting is High variance and low bias.

In our code based on results we get, the linear model has the best performance in predicting which helps us understands that our dataset is linear and fits efficiently in the model.

Pre-Processing Effect¶

In order to find out the influence of pre-proccessing on our model we use the linear model and compare after pre-processing dataframe with the one without reliable pre-proccessing. So we need to use the simple dataframe.

In [183]:
df_no_preprocess = pd.read_csv('train.csv')
for i in df_no_preprocess:
    if df_no_preprocess[i].dtype == 'object':
        df_no_preprocess[i] = df_no_preprocess[i].astype('category').cat.codes
df_no_preprocess = df_no_preprocess.fillna(0)

X = df_no_preprocess.iloc[:, :-1].values
y = df_no_preprocess.iloc[:, -1].values
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20)

regressor = LinearRegression()
regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = regressor.predict(X)
print('Mean Absolute Error:', mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y, y_pred, squared=False))

Mean Absolute Error: 18309.6011526
Mean Squared Error: 29573.6058578

You can see that fillnig all the null features with 0 increase error values.

Voting Regression¶

In [217]:
from sklearn.ensemble import VotingRegressor
X = df.iloc[:, :-1].values
y = df.iloc[:, -1].values
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20)

linear_regressor = LinearRegression()
decision_tree_regressor = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = 12)
knn_regressor = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=8)

er = VotingRegressor([('linear', linear_regressor), ('tree', decision_tree_regressor), ('knn',knn_regressor)])
er.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = er.predict(X_test)
result=pd.DataFrame({'Actual':y_test, 'Predicted':y_pred})
result.head(10)
